Food Labeling and Packaging Safety – Detailed Notes

Introduction

Food labeling and packaging are essential components of food safety and quality management. Packaging protects food from physical damage, chemical contamination, biological hazards, and environmental conditions during handling, storage, transportation, and marketing. Food labeling provides consumers with important information about the product, including its identity, ingredients, nutritional value, storage instructions, expiry date, and manufacturer details.

Proper labeling and safe packaging help consumers make informed choices, reduce food waste, improve product traceability, and ensure compliance with food safety regulations. Regulatory agencies such as the National Agency for Food and Drug Administration and Control (NAFDAC), Codex Alimentarius Commission, the United States Food and Drug Administration (FDA), and the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) establish standards for food labeling and packaging to protect public health.


---

Definition of Food Labeling

Food labeling is the process of providing written, printed, or graphic information on food packaging that informs consumers about the characteristics, composition, nutritional value, safety, and proper use of a food product.

Labels serve as an important communication tool between food manufacturers and consumers and help ensure transparency in the food supply chain.


---

Definition of Food Packaging

Food packaging is the process of enclosing food in suitable materials to protect it from contamination, physical damage, moisture, oxygen, light, insects, and microorganisms during storage, transportation, distribution, and sale.

Packaging helps preserve food quality, extend shelf life, and maintain food safety until consumption.


---

