---

Food Packaging Safety

Packaging materials must be safe for food contact and should not release harmful chemicals into food.

Safe packaging materials should:

Be non-toxic.

Be chemically stable.

Resist moisture and oxygen.

Prevent microbial contamination.

Maintain product quality.

Comply with food safety regulations.



---

Packaging Hazards

Improper packaging may lead to:

Biological Hazards

Microbial contamination

Mold growth

Insect infestation


Chemical Hazards

Migration of harmful chemicals from packaging

Heavy metal contamination

Ink contamination


Physical Hazards

Glass fragments

Metal pieces

Plastic fragments

Packaging defects



---

Modern Packaging Technologies

Modern food packaging includes:

Vacuum packaging

Modified Atmosphere Packaging (MAP)

Active packaging

Intelligent packaging

Aseptic packaging

Edible packaging

Biodegradable packaging


These technologies improve food safety and extend shelf life.


---

Labeling Regulations

Food labels should comply with national and international regulations such as:

Codex Alimentarius Guidelines

NAFDAC Regulations (Nigeria)

FDA Food Labeling Requirements (USA)

European Union Food Information Regulations


These regulations help ensure labels are truthful, accurate, and easy to understand.


---

Good Packaging Practices

Food manufacturers should:

Use food-grade packaging materials.

Maintain hygienic packaging environments.

Inspect packaging materials before use.

Avoid damaged packaging.

Store packaging materials properly.

Seal packages correctly.

Verify label accuracy before distribution.



